WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.797 --> 00:00:11.160
[Music] Good day everyone, I'm Norman Wildberger,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:15.800
and we're talking about box arithmetic&nbsp;
and applying it to number theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:24.080
particularly the Euler product formula for the&nbsp;
zeta function and associated things. For us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:33.240
the central object here is what we call the&nbsp;
fundamental identity of arithmetic, which is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:42.680
identity involving boxes and the caret operation.&nbsp;
We've shown how to take that identity and use it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:48.960
to cook up variants of the Euler product. I&nbsp;
want to go further by talking a little more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:55.040
about multiplicative functions and then applying&nbsp;
them to the situation. Perhaps in the next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.040 --> 00:01:03.040
we'll bring in Dirichlet series into the story.&nbsp;
We're touching base with some pretty fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:10.960
and important ideas from number theory, but&nbsp;
perhaps in a somewhat novel combinatorial way.

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:17.520
The fundamental identity of arithmetic is this&nbsp;
one here: here is the box of powers of two, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:24.000
powers of three, then powers of five, carrying on&nbsp;
over primes. We're taking the caret of all these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:31.280
boxes, and on the right-hand side, we have the&nbsp;
box consisting of all the natural numbers. What&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:38.840
we saw last time is that if you take an integer n,&nbsp;
then you can raise everything to the nth power and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:46.520
still get an identity involving boxes and their&nbsp;
carets. Here we've just taken all of these and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:51.640
raised them to the nth power, raised all of these&nbsp;
to the nth power, and so on, and on the right-hand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:57.440
side, raised the natural numbers to the nth&nbsp;
power. Then we saw that to connect with the Euler&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:04.280
product, we apply this sum operator which takes&nbsp;
one of these boxes and adds up all the elements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:10.760
in the box. So the sum of all these elements, then&nbsp;
times the sum of all these elements, times the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.760 --> 00:02:19.400
sum of all these elements, etc. That should, in&nbsp;
some sense, be equal to the sum of all of these.

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:25.440
When n is a natural number like five,&nbsp;
it appears that none of these things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:35.560
make immediate sense. But if n is a negative&nbsp;
number like minus five, then these sums here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:44.480
according to classical analysts, converge. They&nbsp;
don't actually converge to me because I'm not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:49.280
allowing infinite arithmetical processes,&nbsp;
but nevertheless, the standard story is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:55.960
that if you took n to be say minus eight,&nbsp;
then you would get a legitimate identity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.960 --> 00:03:02.320
and that's essentially the Euler product. The&nbsp;
crucial thing here is the multiplicative aspect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:08.240
of this taking powers operation. We want to&nbsp;
exploit that and investigate multiplicative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:14.400
functions more generally so we can cook&nbsp;
up variants to this important example.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:19.560
What made the previous example work is the&nbsp;
multiplicative property of taking a power,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:26.520
that a * b to the n is equal to a to the n *&nbsp;
b to the n for general natural numbers a and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:34.080
b. This motivates us to define the following: a&nbsp;
strongly multiplicative function from the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:39.000
numbers to the natural numbers, or perhaps&nbsp;
from the natural numbers to the integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.560
is a function that satisfies this basic property&nbsp;
that f of a * b equals f of a * f of b. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:55.640
example, raising a number to the nth power is an&nbsp;
example of a strongly multiplicative function.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.640 --> 00:04:04.160
Somewhat weaker than that is just the notion of&nbsp;
a multiplicative function. It’s the same story,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:10.080
we have the same condition that f of a * b&nbsp;
equals f of a * f of b, but now we require&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:16.760
only that it works when the numbers a and&nbsp;
b are relatively prime natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:26.240
in other words, when they don't have any&nbsp;
common factors, their gcd (greatest common&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:32.480
divisor) is one. This is a weaker condition,&nbsp;
meaning there are going to be more of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:38.080
multiplicative functions than there are&nbsp;
strongly multiplicative functions. It will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:44.720
turn out that just multiplicative functions&nbsp;
are enough for us to make this story work,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:49.680
and it's pleasant because there are actually&nbsp;
quite a lot of really interesting multiplicative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.680 --> 00:04:55.600
functions that play an important role in&nbsp;
number theory, even in classical number theory.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:59.920
Let’s talk about some important&nbsp;
multiplicative functions. One of them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:08.200
is the Möbius function, which is very simple. A&nbsp;
natural number is sent to either one, minus one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:15.000
or zero. It’s sent to zero if it has a squared&nbsp;
prime factor in it, in other words, if one of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:24.080
the primes in its prime decomposition appears&nbsp;
with an exponent greater than one. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:35.360
12 has 2 squared as a factor, so μ(12) will be&nbsp;
zero. If the number does not have any squared&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:43.440
prime factors, meaning all the primes that&nbsp;
appear in the expansion of this number into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:54.680
prime factors are distinct, then μ(n) is one if&nbsp;
there's an even number of such prime factors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.680 --> 00:06:00.120
and it's minus one if there are an odd&nbsp;
number of prime factors. It's not too&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:04.880
hard to see that this is a multiplicative&nbsp;
function, and it plays a big role in number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:09.800
theory. It’s not actually going to be so&nbsp;
important for us for what we're doing today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:16.600
but it will figure importantly when we start&nbsp;
talking about Dirichlet series in a lecture or so.

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:25.800
Another one, the Euler totient function φ(n), is&nbsp;
the number of natural numbers k less than n which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:34.920
are relatively prime to n, in other words, which&nbsp;
don’t have any common factor with n. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:41.560
φ(7) is six because all the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4,&nbsp;
5, and 6, all the natural numbers less than seven,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:47.440
are relatively prime to seven because seven&nbsp;
is a prime. φ(8), on the other hand, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:52.840
the numbers which are less than eight and&nbsp;
relatively prime to it are 1, 3, 5, and 7,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:59.640
and there are four of them, so φ(8) equals&nbsp;
4. The basic rule is that if p is a prime,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:14.760
then φ(p) = p - 1, and φ(p^k) = p^k * (p - 1).&nbsp;
You can think about this in the following way:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:25.200
this is the same as p^k, which is all the numbers&nbsp;
from 1 to p^k minus p^(k-1), which are all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:33.960
multiples of p. All the multiples of p which are&nbsp;
less than or equal to p^k are p * 1, p * 2, p * 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:41.640
etc., all the way up to p * p^(k-1), so there&nbsp;
are p^(k-1) of them. So, you have to take them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:48.880
away, and all the others are relatively prime&nbsp;
to p^k. This is an example where we see it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:55.240
not strongly multiplicative because this thing&nbsp;
here is not the k-th power of this. So, it's not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.240 --> 00:08:01.120
strongly multiplicative, but it is multiplicative&nbsp;
in the sense that this formula here suffices to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:07.480
allow you to calculate φ of any number because&nbsp;
you just decompose this number into prime factors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:13.800
(assuming you can do that), and then you apply&nbsp;
these formulas to each one of those prime factor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:22.680
powers. The result will just be the product of&nbsp;
all of those. This is the Euler totient function.

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:29.720
It’s going to be interesting for us now to apply&nbsp;
this Euler totient function φ to our fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:35.120
identity of arithmetic. Here is our fundamental&nbsp;
identity of arithmetic which you've all seen&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:39.640
quite a lot now. I'm just expanding the natural&nbsp;
numbers on the right-hand side a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:43.800
because it's going to be interesting to see the&nbsp;
values of these various things. What we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.800 --> 00:08:49.000
to do is we're going to apply φ to each element&nbsp;
here, every natural number that you see here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.640
we're going to apply φ to it. So, φ(1) is 1,&nbsp;
φ(2) is 1 because that’s a prime, one less&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:04.640
than it is 1. φ(2^2), well, that’s 2 according&nbsp;
to the formula, that would be 2^(2-1) * (2-1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:10.520
so that's 2. φ(2^3), according to&nbsp;
the formula, that’s 2^(3-1) * (2-1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:22.160
that’s 4. So, we see that we're getting powers of&nbsp;
two here also but sort of staggered. φ(3) is 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:34.960
φ(3^2) is 3 * (3-1), so 3 * 2. φ(3^3) is 3^(3-1)&nbsp;
* (3-1), which is 9 * 2 or 18, etc. Again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:46.240
we get another kind of geometric series, starting&nbsp;
with two, common ratio three. The next one, φ(5),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:58.000
is 4. φ(5^2) will be 5 * 4 which is 20. φ(5^3),&nbsp;
φ(5^3) is 5^(3-1) * 4, so that's 100, and so on.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:07.560
On the right-hand side, the φ of all of these&nbsp;
things is this list here: φ(1) is 1, φ(2) is 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:19.240
φ(3) is 2, φ(4) is 2, φ(5) is 4, φ(6) is 2, and&nbsp;
if we didn’t know that, φ(6), the numbers which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:24.440
are relatively prime to six are just one and five.&nbsp;
Another way of getting that would be to take two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:33.360
and three which are relatively prime, φ(2) is 1,&nbsp;
φ(3) is 2, therefore φ(6) has to be 1 * 2. φ(7) is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:40.040
prime 6. φ(8) we've already talked about, that's&nbsp;
4. φ(9), that's the same as 3^2, we know that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:50.160
6. φ(10), that's the product of φ(2) and φ(5), so&nbsp;
1 * 4, so that's 4. φ(11) is a prime, so φ(11) is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:59.280
10. φ(12), that's the product of φ(3) and φ(4), 3&nbsp;
and 4 are relatively prime, so the product here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:08.680
2 * 2, we get 4. φ(13) would be 12, and so on. Now&nbsp;
we're getting an identity of the carets of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:08.680 --> 00:11:18.440
various things. The statement is, for example,&nbsp;
the fours that appear on the right-hand side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:25.840
namely this one, this one, this one, and this one,&nbsp;
are obtained by carting these boxes and seeing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:31.520
where you get fours. That amounts to how can you&nbsp;
choose a box element here, a box element here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:39.040
a box element here, and so on, so that the&nbsp;
product of all of those is four. 1 * 1 * 4, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:47.960
there's an example, or 1 * 1 * 4, that's another&nbsp;
example, or 4 * 1 * 1, that's another example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:56.880
or 2 * 2 * 1, that's another example,&nbsp;
and I guess maybe that's all there is.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:08.680
That's cool. We have an identity, and we could&nbsp;
apply the sum operation. But on the face of it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:13.960
that's not immediately interesting because&nbsp;
these sums appear like they're all going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:19.760
be divergent. But what we can do is go back and do&nbsp;
exactly the same kind of thing that we did to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:28.880
zeta function story. We could take this identity&nbsp;
and say apply an nth power, still the same idea,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:34.520
we can apply the multiplicative function of&nbsp;
raising something to the nth power and we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:38.920
still going to get an identity exactly of the&nbsp;
same kind. But now we just have to take all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:47.480
of these elements and raise them all to the nth&nbsp;
power, all of them, and that's going to be another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:47.480 --> 00:12:57.160
identity of msets or boxes. If we judiciously&nbsp;
choose n to be a negative of a natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.160 --> 00:13:03.520
the negative of a natural number, then we can&nbsp;
expect, at least classically, that these guys&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:11.040
here, well the entries are getting big, and so if&nbsp;
you raise them to a negative natural number power,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:15.200
you're getting something which gets smaller and&nbsp;
smaller, so there's a chance that this thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:24.440
will converge in some kind of traditional sense.&nbsp;
The same thing will apply to each one of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:30.600
things here, we're going to get geometric series,&nbsp;
in fact. We can write down formulas for them and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:36.000
so we're going to get some kind of identity&nbsp;
very much like an Euler product for the zeta&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.640
function. But now it's quite different because&nbsp;
instead of having the natural numbers down here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:48.480
we have the totient values of the natural&nbsp;
numbers. Let's see what kind of identity we get.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:56.880
Now what we want to do is write down formulas for&nbsp;
the sums of the things that are in these boxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:01.360
So, all of this is the first sum, and then we&nbsp;
multiply by this next sum, and then the next sum,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:06.760
etc. We multiply them all together and we should&nbsp;
get this sum on the right-hand side, at least in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:14.440
some sense. On the left-hand side, we have a&nbsp;
product over primes. What we have is we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:19.960
one. Each one of them starts with one, and then&nbsp;
there's a geometric series. Like this one here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:29.520
a geometric series that starts with (p-1)^n. This&nbsp;
is the p = 5 case, so (p-1)^n, and then there’s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:36.600
it’s just a geometric series built on that where&nbsp;
the common ratio is p^n, or p^n in general.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:45.200
1 + p^n + p^(2n) + p^(3n), etc., the geometric&nbsp;
series. We’re taking the product over all primes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.200 --> 00:14:52.280
that’s what's on the left-hand side of this.&nbsp;
On the right-hand side, we’re summing over the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:58.520
natural numbers k. We’re taking φ(k), those are&nbsp;
these numbers 1, 1, 2, 2, 4, 2, etc., and we’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:05.760
raising them all to the nth power. As I mentioned,&nbsp;
maybe we have a better chance of getting something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:13.120
that looks sort of familiar to us in a convergent&nbsp;
sense if we make n a negative integer, so maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:22.440
we set n = -m, we make this replacement. This n&nbsp;
is replaced with -m, and then it ends up in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:31.840
bottom here, so we get 1 over (p-1)^m. This is a&nbsp;
geometric series, so its sum will be 1 / (1 - the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:38.760
common ratio), which is p^n, but p^n is the&nbsp;
same as p^-n. In the denominator here we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:48.760
(p-1)^m * (1 - p^-m), we’re taking the product of&nbsp;
all of those overall primes. Over here, we just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.760 --> 00:15:58.520
get the sum of the φ(k)s, k running through all&nbsp;
the natural numbers, now raised to this m power.

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:04.680
This is a kind of cool formula, and if you've&nbsp;
been following the lecture, you think, well yeah,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:09.520
we're just applying φ to this fundamental&nbsp;
identity, it's not a surprise. If you've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:15.800
seen the derivation up till now, you say it's not&nbsp;
a surprise, but if I just showed you this formula,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:20.120
showed you the Euler product formula for&nbsp;
the zeta function, and I said, oh here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:24.240
by the way, is something that's a little&nbsp;
bit like that, a little bit different,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:28.920
you might not immediately twig&nbsp;
that this is actually a relatively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:29.720 --> 00:16:35.600
simple kind of consequence of essentially the&nbsp;
same identity that underlies the zeta function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:43.840
story. It looks different, even though it has the&nbsp;
same general form, a product over primes and a sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:51.360
over natural numbers. Here I've rewritten the&nbsp;
formula so we can admire it, and we should ask,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.360 --> 00:16:58.840
well yeah, but is it really true? Is it in&nbsp;
some sense true? Can we check it somehow?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:04.320
Well yes we can, because here we're taking&nbsp;
products and here we're taking sums, and although&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:11.080
these are ongoing, the idea is that if we choose&nbsp;
some m which is a natural number now, then we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.080 --> 00:17:17.880
some kind of convergence. We are expecting that&nbsp;
as we carry on, we're sort of approaching some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:25.360
general value, maybe we're not approaching a real&nbsp;
number but we can just say that as we carry both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:33.080
of these computations on, we should expect that&nbsp;
they start looking close to each other. So we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:33.080 --> 00:17:39.960
check that. Let's check it with m equal to 10 so&nbsp;
we have a reasonably big power down here so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:46.760
these things go to zero reasonably quickly so that&nbsp;
we have a better chance of convergence quickly.

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:57.760
Let's compute this thing here. This is the product&nbsp;
of primes p up to 20: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:07.600
and 19. I've taken those eight products, all of&nbsp;
this form 1 + 1 / (p-1)^10, 1 - p^-10. Of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.600 --> 00:18:12.280
I haven't done it, my computer has done it, and&nbsp;
my computer tells me that this is approximately&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:29.240
2.2933573 dot dot dot. On the right-hand&nbsp;
side, we could take the sum of 1 / φ(k)^10,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.240 --> 00:18:39.040
say k going from 1 to 13, the ones I showed you&nbsp;
already. My computer can calculate that also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.040 --> 00:18:54.320
and it gets 2.2933535. Hey, so that's not bad,&nbsp;
we've got equality up to seven decimal places,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.320 --> 00:19:02.920
that gives us a fair amount of confidence that&nbsp;
this is a reasonable formula. There's something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:07.840
magical about it because on the face of it&nbsp;
these things are very different. Here is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:17.280
product over primes and here is a sum over natural&nbsp;
numbers and we're taking this funny sort of φ,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:27.040
the Euler totient function, to some power. It’s&nbsp;
interesting. Now, has this been studied? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:33.760
I don't know actually, I haven't checked. My guess&nbsp;
is probably number theorists know this, but maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:37.680
it's not well known. Maybe if you're a number&nbsp;
theorist you can tell me if this is well known&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:46.440
or not. In any case, I just want to suggest to&nbsp;
you that this is one of many possible Euler type&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:52.240
formulas that we could cook up without really that&nbsp;
much work, just by taking the fundamental identity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:59.480
of arithmetic and applying some convenient, in&nbsp;
this case, sequence of multiplicative functions to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.480 --> 00:20:04.720
all the entries. That's what we did, we took the&nbsp;
totient function and then we raised things to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:12.440
power, so we actually performed two multiplicative&nbsp;
functions on the elements of the identity.

00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:20.160
We need more multiplicative functions, so here are&nbsp;
some more very common and important multiplicative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:25.640
functions coming from number theory. I just&nbsp;
remind you that multiplicative here doesn’t mean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.640 --> 00:20:32.360
strongly multiplicative, so it means that when you&nbsp;
apply one of these things to powers of a prime,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.360 --> 00:20:39.040
you have to have a separate formula for each&nbsp;
power, but that's enough for us to be able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:46.520
apply the story to our fundamental identity. The&nbsp;
divisor count function, where d(n) is just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:55.000
number of divisors of natural number n. For&nbsp;
example, 6 has 1, 2, 3, and 4 as divisors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:56.640 --> 00:21:06.640
and the number in this set is 4. Here’s what the&nbsp;
function looks like for numbers 1 through 20:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:17.320
d(1) is 1, d(2) is 2, d(3) is 2, d(4) is 3, etc.&nbsp;
You just have a look. The number of divisors of n.

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:23.920
Another kind of related thing is the sum of the&nbsp;
divisor function σ(n). This is the sum of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.920 --> 00:21:37.760
divisors of n. In summation notation, σ(n) is&nbsp;
the summation over d dividing n of d. A crucial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:49.160
property is that σ(p^k) is 1 + p + p^2 + all&nbsp;
the way up to p^k. That’s a geometric series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.160 --> 00:21:57.920
so the formula is (p^(k+1) - 1) / (p - 1). If&nbsp;
you know this formula for a power of a prime,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:03.320
then you can pretty easily calculate&nbsp;
σ(n) for n a natural number as long as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:11.160
you know the prime factorization of n.&nbsp;
That's another multiplicative function.

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:16.640
There's a variant to that. Somewhat more&nbsp;
generally, we can also look at the sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:28.760
of the k-th powers of the divisors of n. So&nbsp;
σ_k(n) is the sum over all d dividing n of d^k,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:40.000
the sum of powers of divisors. When k is zero,&nbsp;
you’re just counting them, and then that's really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.920
this one here. When k is one, you’re taking the&nbsp;
ordinary sum, that's this one here. This is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:53.600
generalization of these other ones. These are&nbsp;
all multiplicative functions, so in principle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.600 --> 00:23:01.760
we can play the same game that we just played&nbsp;
with the totient function for any one of them.

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:08.400
In summary, there are lots of opportunities&nbsp;
for cooking up Euler type product formulas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:12.520
with the general idea being that we start&nbsp;
with the fundamental identity of arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:18.400
namely this thing here, consisting of&nbsp;
boxes, one associated to each prime&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:24.400
number on the left and the box of all natural&nbsp;
numbers on the right. Then we apply various&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:31.680
multiplicative functions to all the elements,&nbsp;
and then after that, we sum up the elements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:40.120
by applying the S operator which converts&nbsp;
these boxes into sums, potentially numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:48.120
and converts the carets into ordinary products. So&nbsp;
we have a product of sums for all of these boxes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:56.440
equaling some sum over the natural numbers&nbsp;
of whatever it is that we're looking at.

00:23:56.960 --> 00:24:03.200
In this story, there’s a helpful tip here which&nbsp;
is that the product of multiplicative functions is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:10.880
also multiplicative, so that means that you could&nbsp;
iterate this story. We’ve already done that once,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:14.800
we already applied the totient function and&nbsp;
then we raised things to a power to try to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:21.360
get something that more easily converges.&nbsp;
We can do the same kind of thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:27.680
but we could in principle iterate this a number&nbsp;
of times and apply one multiplicative function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:34.080
and then another and then maybe another one.&nbsp;
We’re going to get a whole bunch of identities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:41.000
and these identities are maybe interesting,&nbsp;
they’re telling us something about the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:48.520
of numbers. This is not so far from&nbsp;
what number theorists already do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.520 --> 00:24:55.400
this kind of story is not at all far from&nbsp;
standard classical analytic number theory.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:55.400 --> 00:25:01.240
That becomes even more focused when we&nbsp;
shift to Dirichlet series. In my next talk,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:07.280
I want to show you that this box arithmetic point&nbsp;
of view becomes particularly useful when we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:17.280
analyzing convolution of arithmetic functions,&nbsp;
Dirichlet convolutions, and Dirichlet series.

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:28.560
Hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger, thanks for listening.

00:25:28.560 --> 00:25:31.280
[Music]

